english:
  title: Postscript to the Recorded Sayings of Venerable Lazy Monk
  author: Lee Dal-choong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    This records the daily conduct and gestures of the eminent Master Boje, whom the king reveres as teacher. His attendants collected even scattered words and half-verses, compiling them under the title "Recorded Sayings of Venerable Lazy Monk." His disciple Yugok Gakaghong and fellow practitioners sought to publish this work and requested a preface from me. I demurred, saying: "A preface must explain its subject, and to write one without understanding invites ridicule. It is like a blind man leading travelers or a deaf man tuning strings—how could this be right? I know it cannot be. Moreover, with Baekdam's preface already complete, what need is there for my idle words?" Yet Yugok persisted, asking instead for a postscript. Unable to refuse further entreaties, I examined the matter, though I cannot fathom the vastness of this vessel or the clarity of its depths—how could I presume to write of it?

    Yet I have long understood: the Buddha means awakening, and through awakening all sentient beings, compassion becomes the teaching. Is this not the same as our Confucian way—where the awakened awaken the yet-awakened, and benevolence becomes the instruction? Did not our Master once say: "In the west there dwells a great sage who rules without governing, speaks without being disobeyed, acts without commanding, vast and boundless—no name captures him." The Way is one.

    The world says Confucianism and Buddhism contradict each other. Yet I know this contradiction itself errs. Neither this nor that, neither that nor this—their followers simply have not reached the destination. They peddle their wares and denounce each other. But Confucius and Buddha are only one mass of harmonious spirit. Observing this record now, I am convinced of this truth. Casting off illusion to cultivate the genuine, bringing blessing to ruler and nation—this is the measure set forth. Since our sovereign honors this master as teacher, this record should be published to awaken the world.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Boje (普濟尊者): The honorific name of Naong, a prominent Korean Buddhist monk of the Goryeo-Joseon transition period.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Baekdam (白淡菴): Likely refers to another Buddhist master whose preface was already written for this collection.'
  - key: ''
    value: The author invokes Confucian imagery (blind guide, deaf tuner) to express humility about writing on Buddhist matters.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Confucius discussing 'a great sage in the west' reflects the historical encounter between Confucian and Buddhist thought in East Asia, portraying harmony rather than conflict between traditions.
